  "What is a probability density function (pdf)?": "",
  "A function that gives the exact probability of each specific value under most circumstances involving probability": "",
  "Any function that is always between 0 and 1, since standard models of probability behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "A non-negative function whose integral over the entire domain equals 1, used to describe the likelihood of a continuous random variable taking values in various ranges": "",
  "A function that counts the number of outcomes when the interaction between probability and density factors is taken into full account": "",
  "A probability density function (pdf) describes the relative likelihood of a continuous random variable taking on given values. The probability of the variable falling in a range [a, b] is the integral of the pdf from a to b. The pdf must be non-negative and integrate to 1 over its entire domain.": "",
  "What does 'expected value' mean for a continuous random variable?": "",
  "The long-run average value of the variable, computed as the integral of x*f(x) dx": "",
  "The maximum value the variable can take": "",
  "The most likely outcome": "",
  "The value that splits the distribution in half": "",
  "The expected value (or mean) is the long-run average of the random variable over many observations. For a continuous variable, E(X) = integral of x*f(x) dx. It is the 'center of mass' of the probability distribution.": "",
  "What is a cumulative distribution function (CDF)?": "",
  "The reciprocal of the pdf": "",
  "A function that gives the most probable outcome": "",
  "A function that accumulates probabilities: F(x) = P(X <= x), the probability of the variable being at most x": "",
  "The derivative of the probability density function": "",
  "The CDF F(x) = P(X <= x) gives the probability that the random variable takes a value less than or equal to x. It is obtained by integrating the pdf from -infinity to x. It is non-decreasing, starting at 0 and approaching 1.": "",
  "What does 'median' mean for a continuous probability distribution?": "",
  "The value m such that P(X <= m) = 0.5": "",
  "The same as the expected value": "",
  "The average of the minimum and maximum values": "",
  "The value where the pdf is maximized": "",
  "The median m of a continuous distribution is the value that divides the probability in half: P(X <= m) = 0.5. Equivalently, integral from -infinity to m of f(x) dx = 0.5. The median is not necessarily equal to the mean.": "",
  "What is an 'exponential distribution'?": "",
  "A distribution with mean equal to its variance": "",
  "A distribution with pdf f(x) = (1/lambda)*e^(-x/lambda) for x >= 0, often used to model waiting times": "",
  "A distribution where the variable can only be positive integers": "",
  "Any distribution where probabilities grow exponentially": "",
  "The exponential distribution has pdf f(x) = (1/lambda)*e^(-x/lambda) for x >= 0, where lambda is the mean. It is commonly used to model time between events in a Poisson process, such as waiting times. Its mean and standard deviation are both lambda.": "",
  "What does 'standard deviation' mean for a probability distribution?": "",
  "The most common value in the distribution": "",
  "The difference between the maximum and minimum values": "",
  "The probability that a value is within one unit of the mean": "",
  "The square root of the variance, measuring the typical spread of values around the mean": "",
  "The standard deviation sigma = sqrt(Var(X)) is a measure of spread. It has the same units as the random variable and indicates how far values typically deviate from the mean. A smaller standard deviation means values are more concentrated around the mean.": "",
